  "text": "In conclusion, in this study, we documented that mRNFL, mGCL, and mIPL are significantly reduced in MS patients already at the time of diagnosis, that is, likely in early, most inflammatory, stages of the disease, without a concomitant pRNFL thinning; this result may suggest that retinal damage could begin from the macular ganglion cells and might not be secondary to the axonal damage, as currently hypothesized. [CITATION_1] Moreover, OCT outcomes were correlated with patterns of cortical atrophy crucial for visuospatial performance since early stages of the disease. (a) VBM analysis showed significant correlation of GM volume with macular GCIPL thickness in the peristriate cortex and in the parietal cortex (in particular, the angular gyrus). P FWE corr at cluster level < 0.005 and (b) VBM analysis showed significant correlation of GM volume with pRNFL thickness in the visual association cortex, the peristriate cortex and the right cerebellar cortex. P FWE corr at cluster level <0.005.",
